    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "@Haroenv \r\n\r\nNot to resurrect an old issue, but did you ever find a solution for this?\r\n\r\nI spent a few hours searching for this exact thing and at some point pieced together a potential solution from a few different sources. (unfortunately i did not note the sources, so I am unable to give credit. if i find the sources, I will update here)\r\n\r\nIn the hope that this may help someone else, I put together this example:\r\nhttps://codesandbox.io/s/custom-current-refinements-ykcx2\r\n\r\nIn this example, I added a custom `currentRefinements` widget via `connectCurrentRefinements`. (see `src/customCurrentRefinements.js`) The refinement items are altered to separate filters that can contain multiple refinements -- for example, the `refinementList`, which allows multiple selections. However, the `numericMenu` filters stay as one unit and are given an alternate label, showing the range as a single string.\r\n\r\n`[X] 1 - 3` instead of the normal `[X] > 1 [X] < 3`\r\n\r\nThe refinements are being stored as a JSON array in a `data-` attribute on the remove button of the refinement item. When the button is clicked, the handler uses the decoded value of the `data-` attribute to refine the upper and lower range values together.\r\n\r\nI have not tried this with a range input specifically, but I think (hope) the `numericMenu` handling can be adapted for range inputs.\r\n\r\nThis is by no means a fully thought out solution, but may prove useful to start down the right path. I'd love to see someone run with it and come up with a solid reusable solution.",
